Workflow

Introduction

The dataset contains 2,126 rows of 22 features extracted from Cardiotocogram (CTG) exams, which were then classified by three expert obstetritians into 3 classes:

  • Normal

  • Suspect

  • Pathological

Data Wrangling

datafh <- datafh %>% 
  select(fetal_health, `baseline value`, abnormal_short_term_variability , uterine_contractions, fetal_movement)

Rename column

datafh <- datafh %>%
  rename(
    fetalhealth = fetal_health,
    baseline = `baseline value`,
    abnvar = abnormal_short_term_variability ,
    uterinecontractions = uterine_contractions,
    fetalmovement = fetal_movement
  )

The columns are described from the data source as follows:

  • baseline - Baseline Fetal Heart Rate (FHR) (beats per minute)

  • abnormal_short_term_variability - Percentage of time with abnormal short-term variability

  • fetalmovement - Number of fetal movements per second

  • uterinecontractions - Number of uterine contractions per second

Create new categorical variable from fetal_health

Variable fetal health is a class of numeric. We will convert it to a new variable fetal_health2as a class of factor variable.

datafh %>% group_by(fetalhealth) %>% count()

To do that, we usefactor()function. The function will categorize a numerical variable

We will create a new variable fetal_health2, then we will verify the categories of the variable fetal_health2

datafh <- 
  datafh %>% 
  mutate(fetalhealth2 = factor(fetalhealth, 
                      labels = c("normal","suspect","pathological")))
datafh %>% 
  count(fetalhealth2)

Plots

  1. Fetal health Distribution

    # Recreate fetal_health_counts with the new variable names
fetal_health_counts <- datafh %>% count(fetalhealth)
fetal_health_counts$percent <- round(fetal_health_counts$n / sum(fetal_health_counts$n) * 100, 2)

# Define the custom colors
custom_colors <- c('#ffb6c1', '#ffffe0', '#ffcc99')  # Light pink, light yellow, light orange

# Pie chart for fetalhealth
p1 <- ggplot(fetal_health_counts, aes(x = "", y = n, fill = factor(fetalhealth))) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") +
  coord_polar("y") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(percent, "%")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(title = "Fetal Health", fill = "Fetal Health") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors) +
  theme_void()

# Bar chart for fetalhealth
p2 <- ggplot(fetal_health_counts, aes(x = factor(fetalhealth), y = n, fill = factor(fetalhealth))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = n), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(title = "Fetal Health", x = "Fetal Health", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors) +
  theme_minimal()

# Arrange plots in a grid
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2, top = textGrob("Fetal Health Distribution", gp = gpar(fontsize = 20, fontface = "bold")))

Confirm the order of fetal_health2

levels(datafh$fetalhealth2)
## [1] "normal"       "suspect"      "pathological"

However, we would like the pathological as the smallest category. To do that we will use thefct_relevel()function.

datafh <- datafh  %>% 
  mutate(fetalhealth2 = fct_relevel(fetalhealth2, 
                               c("pathological", 'suspect', 'normal')))
levels(datafh $fetalhealth2)
## [1] "pathological" "suspect"      "normal"

Estimation

1. VGAM Package

Our intention to investigate the relationship between baseline, accelarations, uterine contractions, and fetal movement with the outcome variables fetalhealth2. Thus, we will perform multinomial logistic regression model to estimate the relation for 2 models:

  • Model 1: Pathological vs Normal

  • Model 2: Suspect vs Normal

In both models, the reference group is Normal

Single Independent Variable

  1. Baseline
log_baseline <- vglm(fetalhealth2 ~ baseline, 
                 multinomial, data = datafh)
summary(log_baseline)

Multiple Independent Variables

We feel that baseline, accelarations, uterine contractions, and fetal movement are all important independent variables. Hence, we want to fit a model with the three independent variables as the covariates.

mlog <- vglm(fetalhealth2 ~ baseline + abnvar, 
             multinomial, data = datafh)
summary(mlog)
##

Model with interaction term between independent variables

Then, we hypothesize that there could be a significant interaction between uterine contractions and fetal movement. And to test the hypothesis, we extend the multivariable logistic regression model by adding an interaction term. This interaction term is a product between variable uterine contractions and fetal movement.

mlogi <- vglm(fetalhealth2 ~ baseline + abnvar + abnvar*baseline, 
             multinomial, data = datafh)
summary(mlogi)

The interaction term in our model showed p-values above 0.05 (p-values of 0.6, ). As the p-value is bigger than the level of significance at5%and the value of regression parameters for the interaction terms are likely not clinically meaningful, we have decided not to use the model with an interaction term.

2. NNET package

Unlike VGAM::vglm function - where the reference or the base outcome is the largest group (level) - the nnet::multinom uses the smallest group (level) as the reference or base outcome.

Inferences

1. VGAM package

For the inference, we will

  • calculate the95%CI (interval estimates)

  • calculate the p-values (hypothesis testing)

There is no facility inside thebroom::tidy()function to generate confidence intervals for object with classvglm. Because of that we will use thecoef(),confint()andcind(0functions to produce a rather nice table of inferences.

We are going to follow these steps:

  • set the number of digits equal to 2 to limit the decimal numbers

  • return the regression coefficents for all^as an object namedb_fitmlog2

  • return the the confidence intervals for all^as an object namedci_fitmlog2

  • combine the^and the corresponding95%CIs

b_mlog <- coef(mlog)
ci_mlog <- confint(mlog) 
b_ci_mlog <- data.frame(b_mlog,ci_mlog) %>%
  rename("log odds" = b_mlog, "Lower CI" = X2.5.., "Upper CI" = X97.5..)
b_ci_mlog %>% 
  kbl(digits = 2, booktabs = T, caption = "Log odds from multinomial logistic regression") %>%
  kable_styling(position = "center")
Log odds from multinomial logistic regression
log odds Lower CI Upper CI
(Intercept):1 -5.17 -7.66 -2.69
(Intercept):2 -20.22 -22.82 -17.62
baseline:1 -0.03 -0.04 -0.01
baseline:2 0.10 0.08 0.12
abnvar:1 0.11 0.10 0.13
abnvar:2 0.09 0.08 0.10

Afterwards, we willexponentiatethe coefficients to obtain therelative-risk ratio. We then combine the results to the previous table. Finally, we will name the columns of the objecttab_fitmlog2.

rrr_mlog <- exp(b_ci_mlog)
tab_mlog <- cbind(b_ci_mlog, rrr_mlog)
colnames(tab_mlog) <- c('b', 'lower b', 'upper b',
                        'RRR', 'lower RRR', 'upper RRR')
tab_mlog %>%
  kbl(digits = 2, booktabs = T, caption = "Log odds and RRR from multinomial logistic regression") %>%
  kable_styling(position = "center")

  geom_line()

# Merging the two plots -----------------------
ggarrange(data_plot, prob_plot, nrow = 2)

Interpretation

  1. Baseline Variable:

    • Pathological vs Normal:

      • Every increment of 1 unit in the baseline variable, controlling for other factors, the odds of being in the pathological group (in comparison to being in the normal group) change by -0.03 (Adjusted RRR = 0.97, 95% CI: 0.96, 0.99, p-value <0.001). The 95% confidence interval (0.96, 0.99) is narrow and does not include 1, indicating a statistically significant decrease in the odds of being in the pathological group as baseline increases.

    • Suspect vs Normal:

      • Every increment of 1 unit in the baseline variable, controlling for other factors, the odds of being in the suspect group (in comparison to being in the normal group) change by 0.10 (Adjusted RRR = 1.10, 95% CI: 1.08, 1.11, p-value <0.001). The 95% confidence interval (1.08, 1.11) is narrow and does not include 1, indicating a statistically significant increase in the odds of being in the suspect group as baseline increases.

  2. Abnormal Variables (abnvar):

    • Pathological vs Normal:

      • Every increment of 1 unit in the abnormal variables, controlling for other factors, the odds of being in the pathological group (in comparison to being in the normal group) change by 0.13 (Adjusted RRR = 1.14, 95% CI: 1.11, 1.16, p-value <0.001).The 95% confidence interval (1.11, 1.16) is narrow and does not include 1, indicating a statistically significant increase in the odds of being in the pathological group as abnormal variables increase.

    • Suspect vs Normal:

      • Every increment of 1 unit in the abnormal variables, controlling for other factors, the odds of being in the suspect group (in comparison to being in the normal group) change by 0.08 (Adjusted RRR = 1.09, 95% CI: 1.07, 1.10, p-value <0.001). The 95% confidence interval (1.07, 1.10) is narrow and does not include 1, indicating a statistically significant increase in the odds of being in the suspect group as abnormal variables increase.

    2. Plot of predicted probability

    This plot shows the predicted probabilities of each fetal health status as a function of baseline values.

    As the baseline value increases, the probability of fetal health being normal decreases, pathological remains relatively constant with a slight decrease, and suspect increases.
